name: mathd_algebra_192
informal_prefix: /-- If $Q = 11-5i$, $E = 11+5i$, and $D = 2i$, find $Q\cdot E \cdot D$. Show that it is 292i.-/
formal_statement:
theorem mathd_algebra_192 (q e d : ℂ) (h₀ : q = 11 - 5 * Complex.I) (h₁ : e = 11 + 5 * Complex.I)
    (h₂ : d = 2 * Complex.I) : q * e * d = 292 * Complex.I := by
goal:
q e d : ℂ
h₀ : q = 11 - 5 * Complex.I
h₁ : e = 11 + 5 * Complex.I
h₂ : d = 2 * Complex.I
⊢ q * e * d = 292 * Complex.I
header:
import Mathlib
import Aesop

set_option maxHeartbeats 0

open BigOperators Real Nat Topology Rat
natural_language_proof:
To compute \( Q \cdot E \cdot D \), we'll start by finding \( Q \cdot E \):

Given:
\[ Q = 11 - 5i \]
\[ E = 11 + 5i \]

Multiplying \( Q \) and \( E \):
\[
\begin{align*}
Q \cdot E & = (11 - 5i)(11 + 5i) \\
& = 11^2 + (11)(5i) - (5i)(11) - (5i)(5i) \\
& = 121 + 55i - 55i - 25i^2 \\
& = 121 - 25(-1) \quad \text{(since } i^2 = -1 \text{)} \\
& = 121 + 25 \\
& = 146
\end{align*}
\]

Now, multiply the result by \( D \):
\[ D = 2i \]

\[
\begin{align*}
Q \cdot E \cdot D & = 146 \cdot (2i) \\
& = 292i
\end{align*}
\]

**Answer:** 292i
